                            <h1>
                            Reverent and Clean
                            </h1>
                            <h2 class="author">
                                    <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/dallin-h-oaks?lang=eng"><div class="byline" id="">
				<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p2" class="">Elder Dallin H. Oaks</p>
				<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p" class="">Of the Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</p>
			</div></a>   
                                    </h2>
                            <hr>
                        </div><!-- end #details -->
                       
                        <div id="primary">
                            
                            
                            <blockquote class="intro dontHighlight">
                                        <a href="http://lds.org/church/leader/dallin-h-oaks?lang=eng">
                                                        <img id="talkPhoto" src="/bc/content/shared/content/images/leaders/dallin-h-oaks-10.jpg" alt="Dallin H. Oaks" class="img-decor">
                                                    </a>
                                        
                                        
                                        
                                    </blockquote>
                            
                            <span style="display: none" id="article-id">03200_000_020</span>
			<div class="figure">
				
			</div>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p3" class="">Recently our <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/ensign/2003/05/the-importance-of-the-family?lang=eng">family</a> was viewing what was supposed to be a wholesome movie on videotape. Suddenly, one of the actors used a vulgar expression. Embarrassed, we began to smooth this over for our ten-year-old daughter. She quickly assured us that we needn&rsquo;t worry because she heard worse than that every day from the boys and girls at her school.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p4" class="">I am sure most LDS parents have had similar experiences. The nature and extent of profanity and vulgarity in our society is a measure of its deterioration.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p5" class="">I cannot remember when I first heard profane and vulgar expressions in common use around me. I suppose it was from adults in the barnyard or the barracks. Today, our young people hear such expressions from boys and girls in their grade schools, from actors on stage and in the movies, from popular novels, and even from public officials and sports heroes. Television and videotapes bring profanity and vulgarity into our homes.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p6" class="">For many in our day, the profane has become commonplace and the vulgar has become acceptable. Surely this is one fulfillment of the Book of Mormon prophecy that in the last days &ldquo;there shall be great pollutions upon the face of the earth.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/morm/8.31?lang=eng#30" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Morm. 8:31</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p7" class="">The people of God have always been commanded to abstain from language that is profane or vulgar. Latter-day Saints should understand why.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p8" class="">The names of God the Father and his Son, <a class="no-link-style" href="http://mormon.org/jesus-christ">Jesus Christ</a>, are sacred. The prophet Isaiah taught that the Lord will not suffer these names to be dishonored&mdash;&ldquo;polluted&rdquo; as the scriptures say. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/20.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 20:11</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/48.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 48:11</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p9" class="">In the third of the Ten Commandments, the Lord commanded ancient Israel: &ldquo;Thou shalt not take the name of the Lord thy God in vain; for the Lord will not hold him guiltless that taketh his name in vain.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ex/20.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ex. 20:7</a>.) This same commandment was repeated to the Book of Mormon people by the prophet Abinadi (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/13.15?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 13:15</a>) and to each of us through modern prophets. (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/136.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 136:21</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p10" class="">The Doctrine and Covenants gives this example:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p11" class="">&ldquo;Let all men beware how they take my name in their lips&mdash;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p12" class="">&ldquo;For behold, verily I say, that many there be who are under this condemnation, who use the name of the Lord, and use it in vain, having not authority.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/63.61-62?lang=eng#60" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 63:61&ndash;62</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p13" class="">This scripture shows that we take the name of the Lord in vain when we use his name without authority. This obviously occurs when the sacred names of God the Father and his Son, Jesus <a class="no-link-style" href="http://jesuschrist.lds.org/">Christ</a>, are used in what is called profanity: in hateful cursings, in angry denunciations, or as marks of punctuation in common discourse.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p14" class="">The names of the Father and the Son are used with authority when we reverently teach and testify of them, when we pray, and when we perform the sacred ordinances of the priesthood.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p15" class="">There are no more sacred or significant words in all of our language than the names of God the Father and his Son, Jesus Christ.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p16" class="">As we read in the Book of Mormon, after the Savior appeared to the people on this continent he taught them that they must take upon them the name of Christ:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p17" class="">&ldquo;For by this name shall ye be called at the last day;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p18" class="">&ldquo;And whoso taketh upon him my name, and endureth to the end, the same shall be saved at the last day.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.5-6?lang=eng#4" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:5&ndash;6</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p19" class="">He has instructed his followers to call the Church in his name. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.7-8?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:7&ndash;8</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/115.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 115:4</a>.) In our time this is The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p20" class="">The Savior taught that we should begin our prayers by saying, &ldquo;Our Father who art in heaven, hallowed be thy name.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/13.9?lang=eng#8" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 13:9</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/luke/11.2?lang=eng#1" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Luke 11:2</a>.) In the Book of Mormon, the risen Lord gave these further instructions:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p21" class="">&ldquo;Therefore ye must always pray unto the Father in my name;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p22" class="">&ldquo;And whatsoever ye shall ask the Father in my name, which is right, believing that ye shall receive, behold it shall be given unto you.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p23" class="">&ldquo;Pray in your families unto the Father, always in my name, that your wives and your children may be blessed.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/18.19-21?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 18:19&ndash;21</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:7</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/14.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 14:13</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/15.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 15:16</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p24" class="">The scriptures are replete with declarations that the name of Jesus Christ is &ldquo;the only name which shall be given under heaven, whereby salvation shall come unto the children of men.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/6.52?lang=eng#51" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 6:52</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/4.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 4:12</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/25.20?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 25:20</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/31.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 31:21</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/mosiah/3.17?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mosiah 3:17</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p25" class="">The <a class="no-link-style" href="http://lds.org/topic/bible/">Bible</a> has hundreds of references to the name of God, a sacred word which usually refers to God the Father, or Elohim. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/gen/1.1?lang=eng" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Gen. 1:1</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/john/3.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">John 3:16</a>.) The ancient prophets also knew and revered the name of Jehovah, the Holy One of Israel, Jesus Christ, whom the Bible usually refers to as the Lord. (See <a href="http://scriptures.byu.edu/getscrip.php?ID=22947">JST, Ex. 6:3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/abr/1.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Abr. 1:16</a>, <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/abr/2.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Abr. 2:8</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/ether/3.13-14?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ether 3:13&ndash;14</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/isa/43.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Isa. 43:3</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p26" class="">These names were so sacred that the children of Israel were repeatedly commanded not to profane the holy name of their God. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/lev/18.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Lev. 18:21</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/lev/19.12?lang=eng#11" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Lev. 19:12</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/lev/20.3?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Lev. 20:3</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/lev/21.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Lev. 21:6</a>.) One who blasphemed the name of the Lord was commanded to be put to death by stoning. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/lev/24.16?lang=eng#15" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Lev. 24:16</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p27" class="">Cataloging the sins of his countrymen, the prophet Ezekiel said, &ldquo;Her priests have &hellip; profaned mine holy things: they have put no difference between the holy and the profane &hellip; and I am profaned among them.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ezek/22.26?lang=eng#25" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ezek. 22:26</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ezek/36.20-23?lang=eng#19" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ezek. 36:20&ndash;23</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p28" class="">Throughout the ages, the Lord has directed that &ldquo;whatsoever ye shall do, ye shall do it in my name.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/3-ne/27.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">3 Ne. 27:7</a>.) God the Father commanded that Adam and Eve and all of their descendants should be baptized &ldquo;in the name of mine Only Begotten Son, who is full of grace and truth, which is Jesus Christ.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/moses/6.52?lang=eng#51" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Moses 6:52</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p29" class="">At the conclusion of his ministry, the risen Lord identified signs that would follow those who believed (see <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/mark/16.17-18?lang=eng#16" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Mark 16:17&ndash;18</a>):</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p30" class="">&ldquo;In my name they shall do many wonderful works;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p31" class="">&ldquo;In my name they shall cast out devils;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p32" class="">&ldquo;In my name they shall heal the sick;</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p33" class="">&ldquo;In my name they shall open the eyes of the blind, and unstop the ears of the deaf.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/84.66-69?lang=eng#65" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 84:66&ndash;69</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p34" class="">When Peter healed the lame beggar, he spoke these words: &ldquo;Such as I have give I thee: In the name of Jesus Christ of Nazareth rise up and walk.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/acts/3.6?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Acts 3:6</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p35" class="">When the names of God the Father and his Son, Jesus Christ, are used with reverence and authority, they invoke a power beyond what mortal man can comprehend.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p36" class="">It should be obvious to every believer that these mighty names&mdash;by which miracles are wrought, by which the world was formed, through which man was created, and by which we can be saved&mdash;are holy and must be treated with the utmost reverence. As we read in modern revelation, &ldquo;Remember that that which cometh from above is sacred, and must be spoken with care, and by constraint of the Spirit.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/63.64?lang=eng#63" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 63:64</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p37" class="">So it is that the Holy Priesthood after the Order of the Son of God is called the Melchizedek Priesthood &ldquo;out of respect or reverence to the name of the Supreme Being, to avoid the too frequent repetition of his name.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/107.3-4?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 107:3&ndash;4</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p38" class="">The desire and work of Satan is to mislead and corrupt. He seeks to frustrate the gospel plan by which God has provided the opportunity of eternal life for His children.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p39" class="">Satan seeks to discredit the sacred names of God the Father and his Son, Jesus Christ, the names through which their work is done. He succeeds in a measure whenever he is able to influence any man or woman, boy or girl, to make holy names common and to associate them with coarse thoughts and evil acts. Those who use sacred names in vain are, by that act, promoters of Satan&rsquo;s purposes.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p40" class="">Profanity is profoundly offensive to those who worship the God whose name is desecrated. We all remember how a prophet reacted from a hospital bed when an operating room attendant stumbled and cursed in his presence. Even half-conscious, Elder [Spencer W.] Kimball &ldquo;recoiled and implored: &lsquo;Please! Please! That is my Lord whose names you revile.&rsquo;&rdquo; (<span class="emphasis">Improvement Era,</span> May 1953, p. 320.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p41" class="">The words we speak are important. The Savior taught that men will be held to account for &ldquo;every idle word&rdquo; in the day of judgment. &ldquo;For by thy words thou shalt be justified, and by thy words thou shalt be condemned.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/12.36-37?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 12:36&ndash;37</a>.) He also said, &ldquo;That which cometh out of the mouth, this defileth a man.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/15.11?lang=eng#10" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 15:11</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p42" class="">Truly, as the Apostle James taught, &ldquo;The tongue is a fire, &hellip; an unruly evil&rdquo; that can defile the whole body. (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/james/3.6,8?lang=eng#5" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">James 3:6, 8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p43" class="">Profanity also takes its toll on the one who uses it. As we read in Proverbs, &ldquo;A wholesome tongue is a tree of life: but perverseness therein is a breach in the spirit.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/prov/15.4?lang=eng#3" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Prov. 15:4</a>.) The Spirit of the Lord, the Holy Ghost, testifies of God the Father and his Son, Jesus Christ. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/2-ne/31.18?lang=eng#17" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Ne. 31:18</a>.) When those names are dishonored, that Spirit, which &ldquo;doth not dwell in unholy temples&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/hel/4.24?lang=eng#23" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Hel. 4:24</a>), is offended and withdraws. For this reason, those who profane the name of God inevitably relinquish the companionship of his Spirit.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p44" class="">As the Apostle Paul taught Timothy, in order to be &ldquo;approved unto God,&rdquo; we must &ldquo;shun profane and vain babblings: for they will increase unto more ungodliness.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-tim/2.15-16?lang=eng#14" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Tim. 2:15&ndash;16</a>.) Profanity leads to more ungodliness because the Spirit of the Lord withdraws and the profane are left without guidance.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p45" class="">Vulgar and crude expressions are also offensive to the Spirit of the Lord.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p46" class="">The Apostle James taught that followers of Christ should be &ldquo;slow to speak, slow to wrath,&rdquo; and should &ldquo;lay apart all filthiness.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/james/1.19,21?lang=eng#18" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">James 1:19, 21</a>.) In the Bible, filthiness is a term associated with sexual sin and with lewd language. (See <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ezek/16.36?lang=eng#35" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ezek. 16:36</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/ot/ezek/24.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Ezek. 24:13</a>; <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/eph/5.3-4?lang=eng#2" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Eph. 5:3&ndash;4</a>.) Thus, Paul was surely condemning vulgarity when he wrote the Colossians, &ldquo;Also put off all these; anger, wrath, malice, blasphemy, filthy communication out of your mouth.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/col/3.8?lang=eng#7" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Col. 3:8</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p47" class="">These biblical condemnations of vulgarity are needed in our day.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p48" class="">Indecent and vulgar expressions pollute the air around us. Relations that are sacred between husband and wife are branded with coarse expressions that degrade what is intimate in marriage and make commonplace what is forbidden outside it. Moral sins that should be unspeakable are in the common vernacular. Human conduct plunging downward from the merely immodest to the utterly revolting is written on the walls and shouted in the streets. Twentieth-century men and women of sensitivity can easily understand how Lot, a fugitive from the actions and speech of Sodom and Gomorrah, could have been &ldquo;vexed with the filthy conversation of the wicked.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/2-pet/2.7?lang=eng#6" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">2 Pet. 2:7</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p49" class="">How soberly we must regard the Book of Mormon teachings that &ldquo;there cannot any unclean thing enter into the kingdom of God; wherefore there must needs be a place of filthiness prepared for that which is filthy.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/1-ne/15.34?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">1 Ne. 15:34</a>; see also <a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/7.21?lang=eng#20" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 7:21</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p50" class="">Profane and vulgar expressions are public evidence of a speaker&rsquo;s ignorance, inadequacy, or immaturity.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p51" class="">A speaker who profanes must be ignorant or indifferent to God&rsquo;s stern command that his name must be treated with reverence and not used in vain.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p52" class="">A speaker who mouths profanity or vulgarity to punctuate or emphasize speech confesses inadequacy in his or her own language skills. Properly used, modern languages require no such artificial boosters.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p53" class="">A speaker who employs profanity or vulgarity to catch someone&rsquo;s attention with shock effect engages in a babyish device that is inexcusable as juvenile or adult behavior. Such language is morally bankrupt. It also progressively self-defeating, since shock diminishes with familiarity and the user can only maintain its effect by escalating its excess.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p54" class="">Members of the Church, young or old, should never allow profane or vulgar words to pass their lips. The language we use projects the images of our hearts, and our hearts should be pure. As the Savior taught:</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p55" class="">&ldquo;Out of the abundance of the heart the mouth speaketh.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p56" class="">&ldquo;A good man out of the good treasure of the heart bringeth forth good things: and an evil man out of the evil treasure bringeth forth evil things.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/nt/matt/12.34-35?lang=eng#33" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Matt. 12:34&ndash;35</a>.)</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p57" class="">The Book of Mormon teaches us that when we are brought before the judgment bar of God &ldquo;our words will condemn us &hellip; and our thoughts will also condemn us.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/bofm/alma/12.14?lang=eng#13" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">Alma 12:14</a>.) Let us recognize profanity and vulgarity for what they are. They are sins that separate us from God and cripple our spiritual defenses by causing the Holy Ghost to withdraw from us.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p58" class="">We should abstain and we should teach our children to abstain from all such expressions.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p59" class="">We can also encourage our associates to do likewise. Where we have the courage to make a friendly request, like Elder Kimball, we will often receive a respectful and cooperative reply. Our married daughter who lives in Illinois had such an experience. As she took her turn carpooling the twelve-year-olds home from the soccer game, her noisy passengers filled the air with profanity. Firmly, but with good humor, she told the boys, &ldquo;In our family we only use that name when we worship, so we ask you, please don&rsquo;t say that name disrespectfully in our car.&rdquo; The boys immediately complied, and, what is even more surprising, most of them still remembered the next time it was her turn to drive.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p60" class="">We obviously cannot control all that goes on in our presence. Modern revelation suggests one alternative for those who would be clean: &ldquo;Go ye out from among the wicked. Save yourselves.&rdquo; (<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/dc-testament/dc/38.42?lang=eng#41" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">D&amp;C 38:42</a>.) Sometimes we can remove ourselves from language that is profane or vulgar. If this is not possible, we can at least register an objection so that others cannot conclude that our silence means approval or acquiescence.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p61" class="">Our thirteenth article of faith commits us to seek after things that are &ldquo;virtuous, lovely, or of good report or praiseworthy.&rdquo; [<a href="http://lds.org/scriptures/pgp/a-of-f/1.13?lang=eng#12" onclick="newWindow(this.href); return false;">A of F 1:13</a>.] The language of Latter-day Saints should be reverent and clean. We understand the eternal requirement of cleanliness, and we understand the sacred significance of the names of the Father and the Son.</p>
			<p uri="/ensign/1986/05/reverent-and-clean.p62" class="">I testify of God the Father and his Son, Jesus Christ, and pray that we may be more faithful in honoring their holy names. In the name of Jesus Christ, amen.</p>
		
                            
                            
                            
